{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"f3c671e3622493f0843abb26049f341e008a022f777957a5531f697447a0400f","slug":"papers.rram-devices.index","location":"/papers/rram-devices/index.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"RRAM Devices","description":"Resistive RAM, oxide switching, filament formation, sneak currents, crossbar arrays, and in-memory computing.","content_includes_title":false,"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"index.md","url":"/build/index-7a0401a29aeb7306c58efc5a7838f40a.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What is this domain?","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"TZfaSeb335"}],"identifier":"what-is-this-domain","label":"What is this domain?","html_id":"what-is-this-domain","implicit":true,"key":"OpBxZoLEG1"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Resistive random-access memory (RRAM) is a class of non-volatile memory technology in which data is stored as the resistance state of a metal-insulator-metal stack. Switching between high-resistance (HRS) and low-resistance (LRS) states is achieved by the formation and dissolution of conductive filaments — typically composed of oxygen vacancies or metal cations — within a thin oxide layer. RRAM devices are among the most mature memristive technologies and have reached commercial production in several forms.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"umZfKr1plK"}],"key":"NJxP6mKyDr"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Why it matters","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"key":"DHPPTbYprL"}],"identifier":"why-it-matters","label":"Why it matters","html_id":"why-it-matters","implicit":true,"key":"p0FiZddFRJ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"RRAM offers a compelling combination of properties for neuromorphic computing: nanoscale scalability, CMOS compatibility, analogue conductance tuning, low switching energy, and non-volatility. Dense crossbar arrays of RRAM devices can perform vector-matrix multiplication in the analogue domain at the location of weight storage, eliminating the von Neumann bottleneck and enabling in-memory computing at a fraction of the energy cost of digital approaches.","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"TzzHRREdVH"}],"key":"hwbjs3HSBo"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Core concepts","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"nYrHWh0Nq7"}],"identifier":"core-concepts","label":"Core concepts","html_id":"core-concepts","implicit":true,"key":"n3bMKY8tvg"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Filamentary switching mechanism","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"LV0ZFtHvz4"}],"key":"aeMsWcq0Zc"},{"type":"text","value":" — set (LRS) and reset (HRS) transitions involve the formation and rupture of nanoscale conductive filaments driven by Joule heating, ion drift, and redox reactions","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"ocJtHrF8Nx"}],"key":"RTor10l481"}],"key"